<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / World Bank says other solutions must be found to poverty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Slower population growth will not be enough to solve the problem of poverty
in developing nations, the World Bank says in a report prepared for next
week's United Nations population conference in Cairo, writes George Graham
in Washington.
Although slowing down the rate of population growth should still be a high
priority for developing countries, the report says, a broader programme
involving investment in education, health and nutrition will be needed to
address poverty.
'We need to combine reproductive health and family planning with better
infant and child health, education of girls and overall improvement in the
status of women,' said Mr Armeane Choksi, the bank's vice-president for
human resource development and operations policy. The bank expects world
population to grow over the next 35 years to around 8.5bn, with almost 90
per cent of the rise occurring in developing countries.
