<PROFILE>_AN-EH2B3AEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940829
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Business Travel: The anatomy of a Club Class flight -
Millions of people travel business class each year. But few are aware of
what goes into providing the extra services. Charles Jennings visited
British Airways to explore  ..
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES JENNINGS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Air-conditioning
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The air enters the cabin from the cabin side walls, above head height
and below the overhead lockers, and is extracted from the side walls at
floor level. There are three air-conditioning units on each 747,
changing the 51,950 cubic feet of air in the entire passenger area
every three minutes and keeping it at a constant temperature of about
70'F (some airlines, it is rumoured, only run two of the three air-con
units at a time in order to save fuel, but at the expense of
freshness). To keep it clean, the air is filtered through paper filters
which are changed every 6,360 flying hours. Cigars, of course, are not
allowed: no air-conditioning unit can cope with the smell.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Windows
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
These are made of three separate acrylic panes. The outer two are load
carrying, while the inner is simply a protective panel. There is an
air-gap between each pane. Normally, the outer pane carries the full
load of pressurisation. If the outer pane should fail, the middle pane
panes are designed to take at least twice the maximum normal cabin
pressure on their own: equivalent to a load of over a ton on a single
pane. It does not matter if the inner pane is scratched or accidentally
damaged, as it does not take any pressurisation load. Thus the risk of
doing a 'Goldfinger' and being sucked out at 50,000 feet is slim.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pressurisation
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Fresh air is drawn into the plane from ducts on the fuselage, heated
and pressurised to around 8 lbs per square inch. This is equivalent
to the air pressure found at the top of an 8,000ft mountain. There is
no risk attached to this, but it does make it difficult to boil water
(as the air pressure drops, so the temperature at which water will boil
rises) and BA flights have been known to carry special cooking units
for passengers who have especially requested boiled eggs.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Baggage hold
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
This is pressurised, but not usually ventilated (unless livestock is
being carried). Thus, the baggage travels throughout the flight in the
air in which it took off. It is loaded in containers shaped to fit the
contours of the plane, swivelled round on a platform of chrome
ball-bearings which line the floor and then pushed down to the far end
of the hold by rams built into the hold bulkhead. The emergency oxygen
supply cylinders are also located beneath the cabin floor; the oxygen
being piped up into overhead masks in the cabin.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Cabin floor
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Inside the cabin, 70 square metres of carpeting are used to cover the
floor of Club World, with the same area of foam underlay (principally to
give passengers the impression they are walking on a thicker pile carpet
then they actually are). The aisle carpets (which receive the heaviest
wear) are replaced every three months; the rest have to make do with
hoovering until the next major redecoration.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Seats
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
There are between 60 and 70 seats in the Club World section of a
747-400, all made of aluminium, with steel used at points of extra
stress. The backs will recline at an angle of up to 38 degrees to the
vertical, they can withstand a 9G static loading and there is no
passenger heavy enough to break them. Moreover, all Club World seats
were recently recovered in 17 miles' worth of wool fabric.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Lifejackets
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Each seat has a lifejacket under it. These lifejackets are checked
every 310 flying hours (coinciding with a particular maintenance
check). To date, however, no commercial passenger jet aircraft has had
to ditch into the sea. So no one has ever used the lifejackets in the
circumstances for which they were designed.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Food facts
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Food and drink consumption: The chilled food is heated in the galleys,
using conventionsal fan-assisted ovens, not microwaves. In a typical
year, Club World passengers will ge through 50 tonnes of lobster, 84
tonnes of salmon, 120 tonnes of beef and 2 tonnes of caviar. More
prosaically, they will also use up 30 litres of mustard, 5,000 portions
of cheese biscuits and 1.5m individual chocolate boxes. Club World also
gets through 250,000  bottles of champagne, selected from a number of
different champagne producers. On every flight, there will be nearly
3,000 items packed on to Club World trays; the chinaware is Royal
Doulton.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Entertainment
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The seat backs now carry individual 6in x 7in LCD colour video screens
with a compensation mechanism to allow for variations in the angle of
the seat back relative to the viewer. There are eight video channels,
allowing for 54 hours of video per flight. The cabling for the video
and audio channel control, and for the overhead light switch and call
button, travels up one of the main seat legs and along a tube located
across the bottom of the seat backs.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Hand washbasins
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
These do empty out into the air, rather than into a holding tank - the
source of those myths about home counties housewives catching Beri-Beri
from a passing plane. The waste water emerges through two drainpipes
beneath the aircraft - one just ahead of the wings, the other at the
tail. Both drainpipes are kept heated, to prevent them from freezing.
1.3m tablets of soap are used up every year.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Blankets, washbags, headsets etc.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Reflecting the fact that business people are more likely to be male than
female, BA gives out 1,032,500 men's washbags each year; and 462 women's
washbags. 63,000 blankets are used (each being washed several times
before being replaced), as well as 400,000 headsets and 324,000 napkins.
The equivalent  of 20 tonnes of aromatic petals go into the essentce
dupplied in Club amenity bags.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Lavatories
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
There is one lavatory for every 18.5 passengers, each lavatory serviced
by a tank holding 16 litres of water. On average, one passenger in five
will produce what are known as 'solids' during a flight, approximately a
quarter of a pound's worth. More generally, every passenger can expect
to produce a pound of liquid during a flight, In the unlikely event that
a lavatory should fill up, sensors warn the cabin crew, which then shuts
the lavatory down.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Food storage &amp; preparation
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Food is heavily chilled before loading on to the plane, then kept in
special cold boxes, refigerated with dry ice. On average, a 747
long-haul flight will be loaded with a total of 4.5 tonnes of food and
drink (or 61,000 individual items) before take-off. The food itself is
prepared for BA by its own in-house long-haul catering unit at Heathrow
 -Catering Centre South; the largest kitchen in Europe. The contents of
the basic menu selection change every three months, but at any given
time, there are 180 different menus in circulation, each tailored to
regional differences in language, culture and diet.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Holding tanks
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The waste material is sucked down the lavatory by a vacuum system,
passed along a pipe, and is collected in four holding tanks at the rear
of the plane. Older 747s use 'recirculating toilets' in which the waste
matter is broken down by powerful chemicals and the resulting blue
water is reused to flush the lavatories. At the end of the flight, the
holding tanks are pumped out by a special ground vehicle. To cope with
all this activity, Club World gets through just under 1m rolls of
lavatory paper a year.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: British Airways
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<XX>
