<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Emerging Markets: Credit squeeze leaves China lower - The
Emerging Investor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After a burst of activity earlier this month, which sent share prices
rocketing, China's fledgling stock markets have slid back under the weight
of negative economic news and poor interim results for listed companies.
Shanghai's B-share index for foreign investors is down by about 6 per cent
from its month's high, finishing last week at 77.71. A-shares for local
investors have also slipped.
Foreign brokers say that a credit squeeze, imposed last year to calm an
overheating economy, is continuing to have a negative impact on company
earnings, and circumstances seem unlikely to improve in the short term.
Government anti-inflation efforts were set back by a jump in retail prices
in July after the rate of price increases appeared to be slowing. Another
worrying development was a leap in capital spending in July, in spite of
government attempts to restrain investment in fixed assets as part of its
anti-inflation strategy.
While sentiment among foreign investors had improved in recent months, poor
results for the six months to June, combined with uncertainties over the
economy, are certain to be giving fund managers pause for thought.
In Shanghai, Mr Paul Vibert, an analyst at Baring Securities, said the
outlook was still very shaky.
The B-share index - B-shares are denominated in yuan but are traded in US
and Hong Kong dollars - had picked itself off the floor, after falling by
about 40 per cent this year. It is now down by about 22 per cent for the
year.
Brokers had expected B-shares to recover their lost ground by the end of
1994, the index finishing at about 100, where it began the year. This now
seems difficult in the light of faltering performances by many of the 28
listed B-share companies.
Earnings, even allowing for excessively optimistic revenue projections for
newly-listed stocks, were little short of disastrous with a couple of
notable exceptions, including Pilkington Glass, whose performances matched
expectations.
At least half the B-share companies failed to achieve targets, and in a
number of cases, such as Forever Bicycle, earnings were much less than
forecast. The worst performing sectors were textile machinery and other
light industrial equipment.
China's problems with 'triangular debt' - the inability of one faltering
enterprise to pay another for goods and services - have almost certainly
contributed to the poor results.
Underlining a slowdown after this month's almost frenzied burst of activity,
with the A-share index more than doubling after the authorities intervened
to prop-up a collapsing market, is the fall in trading volumes. Last week
volume was down to between Yn3bn and Yn4bn compared with a daily turnover of
Yn10-12bn two weeks ago. In the light of a tricky period ahead for the
government economically, with pressures intensifying for stronger medicine
to curb inflation, stock market activity seems likely to continue to be
subdued.
But brokers believe a melt-down similar to last year's when disappointed
local investors deserted the market, is unlikely, especially if the
authorities continue to extend credit to securities houses and also maintain
a ban on new listings. Heavy buying by local institutions is believed to
have been behind the recent surge in A-shares.
'The A-share market appears to be consolidating a little bit,' said Mr
Vibert. 'Local investors appear to have regained confidence.'
For the B-share market, the picture is different in that external factors
are almost as important for market sentiment as local developments. The
market performance of Hong Kong-listed mainland companies, so-called
H-shares, has a direct bearing on the demand for B-shares.
The perception of China investments is also being guided by the reception
given to a dribble of Chinese listings in New York. The initial reaction
could at best be described as wary.
Both the A and B markets are continuing to be bedevilled by confusion over
the regulation of China's markets. The China Securities Regulatory
Commission is nominally in charge, but other bodies such as the People's
Bank of China, the central bank, and State Council, the cabinet, are also
involved. Co-ordination is poor.
In the absence of a securities law, defining regulatory responsibilities,
uncertainty prevails.
