<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Russians plan gold securities market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Russian government is backing plans to create a domestic securities
market for gold bullion, aiming to establish an internal price for the
precious metal and to raise capital to develop one of the country's most
important but troubled industries.
Following a gold industry conference in Moscow last week, government
departments, banks and mining companies plan to establish a non-commercial
Gold Club to co-ordinate the industry's activities and create a secondary
market for gold. Industry officials say such a market could raise Dollars
1bn (Pounds 649m) for much-needed investment.
Preliminary proposals envisage the creation of a class of securities,
similar to western gold warrants, denominated in grammes of gold and freely
traded by legitimate investors. The market would set the official price of
gold within Russia and would be used by the Central Bank and tax
authorities.
The Gold Club has not yet worked out how this exchange could work in
practice nor how soon. A founding meeting of the club will be held next
month.
Mr Valery Skripchenko, head of administration at the Russian Committee for
Precious Metals and Stones, said there were still 'contradictions between a
state which did not wish to relinquish its control of an important strategic
sector of the economy and alternative investors who would not commit
resources to a sector under a permanent threat of nationalisation'.
Industry figures suggest that a gold securities market might reconcile the
differing priorities of the state and outside investors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
