<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Government to forgo profits from National Grid sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has rejected calls from its backbenchers to take a share of
the profits from next year's sale or demerger of the National Grid.
The electricity transmission company is owned by the 12 regional electricity
companies (recs) of England and Wales, which were given it when they were
privatised in 1989. Analysts estimate the company may be worth Pounds 5bn.
The government owns a golden share in the National Grid which allows it to
demand a share of the profits when it is sold or demerged next spring. Some
Tory MPs have urged ministers to use the golden share to extract up to
Pounds 2bn for the Treasury. However, in a move that will further boost the
electricity companies' profitability, the Treasury has argued it would be an
improper use of its golden share, which it says was only intended to prevent
foreign ownership of the grid.
While ministers are privately angry over the large salaries and share
options awarded to electricity company chiefs, they do not believe the
government should intervene in the running of a private industry.
The government's decision has infuriated some of its own backbenchers as
well as provoking criticism from the Labour party. Mr Robin Cook, the shadow
trade and industry secretary, said: 'I see absolutely no reason why the recs
should milk a fortune out of the National Grid that was built by the nation
and not by them.
'Shareholders in the recs would receive from the sale of the grid almost as
much as it cost them to pay for the whole industry when it was privatised.
If the National Grid is sold, the public must get its share.'
Mr Nicholas Winterton, Conservative MP for Macclesfield, warned that voters
were losing patience with the privatised utilities. 'For the government to
hand over the grid lock, stock and barrel to the shareholders of electricity
companies is hardly popular capitalism,' he said.
Mr Richard Caborn, Labour's chairman of the Commons' trade and industry
committee, has asked Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
what protection, if any, was given to taxpayers when the National Grid was
handed over to the recs and why they will not be receiving anything from the
flotation or demerger.
PowerGen shares plan provokes ministers, Page 5
See Lex
</TEXT>
