<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you are not keen on either cosy middlebrow nostalgia or the stuff
endlessly extruded these days by Hollywood, then you might be best advised
to ignore television today and opt instead for a restaurant or the cinema.
If cash flow is sticky you could try a nice long bath and lots of radio.
Those with 3 1/2 hours to spare can hear the Glyndebourne 'Don Giovanni' in
BBC Proms 1994 (7.00 Radio 3). Or at 7.45 Radio 4 offers Lillian Hellman's
1935 play The Children's Hour, about accusations of lesbianism in an
American girls' school. If you are keen on cosy middlebrow nostalgia then
you are in clover. Following on from Saturday's tribute to Lew Grade, the
two BBC channels offer a host of old ATV programmes beginning at 5.00 with
episodes from four series: Sir Francis Drake (1962); The Buccaneers (1956)
with Robert Shaw as the reformed pirate Dan Tempest; The Adventures Of
William Tell (1958); and, most successful of them all, The Adventures of
Robin Hood with Richard Greene in the title role. At 10.30 BBC1 screens an
episode of The Saint starring Roger Moore, followed by Jason King, the Peter
Wyngarde series (11.20).
</TEXT>
