<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / This Week: Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN WRAIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tennis
August 29 to September 11, US Open Tennis Championships, Flushing Meadow,
New York
The richest tennis tournament of the year starts today. Record prize money
of Dollars 9.36m is at stake on the unyielding hard courts at the US
National Tennis Center - an arena famed for testing competitors' fitness and
sapping their stamina. That may be a daunting thought for top seed Pete
Sampras as he attempts to become the first man since Jimmy Connors (1974)
and Mats Wilander (1988) to win three Grand Slam titles in the same year.
Sampras is still suffering from the effects of an ankle injury at Wimbledon.
Andre Agassi will be the people's choice. But watch out for back-in-form
Boris Becker, coming off recent tournament wins in Los Angeles and New
Haven.
Motor Racing
August 30, Michael Schumacher appeal in Paris
Schumacher's bid to become the youngest world motor racing champion suffered
a severe blow yesterday when the 25-year-old German was disqualified for a
rules infringement after passing the chequered flag first in the Belgian
Grand Prix. He could face another setback on Tuesday, when he appeals to the
Federation Internationale de l'Automobile's Court of Appeal against the
two-race suspension imposed last month for ignoring a black flag during the
British Grand Prix. He will have in mind the fate of Eddie Irvine who
earlier this year appealed against a one-race ban for his part in a
three-car collision in Brazil. Irvine left Paris with his suspension
increased to three races.
Cricket
September 3, NatWest Trophy Final, Lord's, London
Victory in the NatWest final will be the next step in Warwickshire's bid to
pull off an unprecedented sweep of all four major English cricket
competitions in a season. The county is well placed to take both the County
Championship and the Sunday League. Warwickshire's opponents on Saturday are
Worcestershire, the team they beat in the Benson and Hedges Cup.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
