<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By  ALKARIM JIVANI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The oldest profession in the world makes use of modern mass media to make
its point. An Open Space Special shown at a post-post watershed hour
(Tuesday 11.15-11.55, BBC2) is given over to John Bratherton, 26, a
Cambridge philosophy graduate who has made a career decision to go into
prostitution. The programme begins in shadow, with Bratherton's identity
disguised, but within seconds he's had enough. And that is the point he is
trying to make: that the clandestine, murky view of his world is not
entirely accurate and he wants to balance that picture by appearing on
television. We see Bratherton, punting down the Cam, and there is even an
interview with the other kind of punter - a married man with a family. It's
a brave film to make not least because the Inland Revenue might be watching.
The latest and most dreaded management buzzword - 'upward appraisal' - is
analysed in The Business (Thursday, 7.30-8.00, BBC2). The theory is that if
employees turn the tables on their bosses and anatomise their performance it
will lead to better performance all round. Federal Express has been using it
for over a decade and is zealous about its efficacy - a bad report can
affect a manager's pay, bonuses and long-term survival. WH Smith and BP are
at the early stages of introducing it and the cameras snoop on a
denunciation session where a BP manager is subjected to a critique by his
colleagues.
The programme claims that upward appraisal is a powerful weapon for those
with a grudge against the boss and that in many companies managers are
feeling like marked men. Alas there are no interviews with any of them.
A marked man who is very much in evidence is Colin Firth in a new series of
The Ruth Rendell Mystery (Friday 9.00-10.00, ITV), which begins with Master
of the Moor in which Firth is Stephen Walby, the chief suspect in a murder
hunt. As a child, Stephen dreams that he comes across a corpse on the moors,
and then another, and another. To his horror, his dreams come true and the
police believe that he is the man responsible. Although not as engaging as
the Wexford series, all of which have now been filmed and transmitted, this
will not disappoint Rendell fans. For those for whom only Wexford will do,
the good news is that Rendell is writing another and plans to film it are
already in progress.
Firth's first major TV appearance was in Tumbledown, the Charles Wood play
about a Falkland veteran which created vast controversy. Now Wood has come
up with another play about soldiers, A Breed of Heroes (Sunday 9.30-11.00,
BBC1), which begins a new season of Screen One. Adapted from the novel by
Alan Judd, the piece, set in Belfast in 1971, is a comedy drama in which our
hero, played by Samuel West, has to take over from the battalion press
officer who has shot himself in the foot - literally. The actors were given
several weeks army training, with the officers separated from the other
ranks - and it shows.
Alkarim Jivani
TV editor of Time Out
</TEXT>
