<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Sport: The myth that leads to drugs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday the Commonwealth Games ended their two-week hold over Victoria,
Canada and BBC television. When I was growing up, this short reign seemed to
have a tremendous importance - second only to that of the Olympics, and cast
in the same grand mould. To win a Commonwealth Games title was highly
impressive and, whatever its colour, a Games medal had true prestige.
Now these titles look like something quaint. Top athletes compete for them
in a spirit of benign patronage, bestowing themselves upon their event
rather as they might visit an ageing great aunt. If by some terrible fluke
their medal is not gold, then it might as well have come out of a cracker
for all the pleasure it gives them to receive it.
Athletics has changed so much since the mid-1980s that it is hard, too, for
the spectator to show the deference of old towards the Commonwealth Games.
Accustomed as one is to seeing world class line-ups at the flick of a
switch, it is impossible to take a proper interest in athletes whom one has
never heard of, and whom one will never lay eyes on again after the race.
Impossible, too, not to feel the absurdity that places nonentities side by
side with superstars, and pits genuine amateurs against amateurs who have
mysteriously earned hundreds of thousands of pounds. Athletes are competing
in the same arena but in two different spheres: that of good club runner and
the other of the world class talent. If an owner were to enter a greyhound
in a 400 metre race against dogs capable of running two seconds faster,
people would think him insane. In athletics however, this seems to be quite
acceptable.
What I love is the way the commentators strive towards egalitarianism.
Moving through the line-up for the race, the degree of quavery respect in
David Coleman's voice will remain the same whether he is introducing Colin
Jackson, or, let us say, Nifty Mwambe in lane eight - 'now 36, was a Zambian
youth champion'. Of course commentators can rightly do nothing else. But
still I like to hear them do it; it seems so mannerly, somehow, like
watching a man be as politely flirtatious with a plain woman as with a
pretty one.
The Commonwealth Games are mannerly. They retain the grace and good humour
that I remember from years ago, and this can be seen in the demeanour of the
athletes - no Dennis Mitchell's here. The superstars seem far happier than
usual; partly, of course, because they are more likely than usual to win,
but also, perhaps, because they are in closer contact than usual with their
club running roots.
It is strange really. In a sense one feels that, despite the vast disparity
between Colin Jackson and Nifty Mwambe, this event brings them together and
suffuses them with the same spirit. In another sense one wonders what the
hell they are doing running against each other. Yes, the superstars are
relaxed, more like real people than the highly-defined images that they have
become to us. But this charming event is not the reality of their lives. The
reality is something much more intense. It is an inescapable part of a much
tougher modern world, and in it they are playing for much higher stakes.
Over the past few years athletes have become, en masse, a phenomenon. They
have come to define an absolute of physicality, which is a quality so
worshipped by our society that the athletes too are worshipped, not merely
for what they do but for what they are: young, fit, dedicated, successful.
Encouraged by the money men, who recognised and exploited this phenomenon,
athletes now act the part for their worshippers. Can you remember how they
used to look, those white shorts flapping like handkerchiefs, those dank
cotton vests, those unselfconscious bodies that never advertised the feats
of which they were capable? Compare them with the glistening peacocks of
today, strutting in their second skin of virulent lycra, and full of the
sense that they are the cynosure of millions of envious eyes. In fact
athletes seem as fascinated by their physicality as we are; together we
collude in forcing the myth that they are almost god-like.
If this myth clings lightly to every athlete, then it positively embraces
the superstars. This is a heavy burden to bear, for all the rewards it
brings. It is very nice to be worshipped. However, when expectations are not
just high but almost unreal, failure assumes an inappropriate significance:
if either Jackson, Christie or Gunnell had lost at the Commonwealth Games,
obituaries of their talent would have been written immediately.
Meanwhile, the mass of unknowns, standing in the lanes around them, yearn
towards their deified image; yearn to leap the cavern that separates
nonentities from superstars. Is it any wonder that there are those within
the world of athletics who will do anything to enhance their abilities?
Probably only if the myth of the god-like athlete were to be exploded would
the problem of drugs disappear.
And, paradoxically, if anything were to explode the myth, it would be the
drug people. The extraordinary recent success of athletics has fed a monster
within it. Watching the Commonwealth Games, one had the oddest sense that
those past and present of athletics were there at the same time; events were
conducted in true, uplifting, amateur spirit, yet who knew if any of the
athletes were what they seemed? One had the sense too, that if athletics
were to have a decent future, free of the taint that now touches both guilty
and innocent, then it would do well to look to its past for guidance.
</TEXT>
<XX>
