<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / This Week: Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Those London audiences lucky enough to have seen the Royal Opera's
production of Die Meistersinger von Nurnberg, one of Covent Garden's
unequivocal successes of last season, will enjoy the first-ever digital
recording of one of Wagner's more tuneful works, conducted by the
highly-experienced Wagnerian, Wolfgang Sawallisch on EMI. Excellent
performances by Bernd Weikl as Sachs, Ben Heppner as Walther and Cheryl
Studer as Eva are memorably backed by the Bayerische Staatsoper orchestra
and chorus.
Those latter-day Meistersingers, Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo and Luciano
Pavarotti, chose a suitably demotic setting, the Dodger Stadium in Los
Angeles, in which to repeat the triumph of their World Cup celebration in
1990. The Three Tenors in Concert 1994 (Teldec) is trailed as a recording of
'the biggest concert in the world', a grandiose claim seemingly untroubled
by the possibility that many of the 1bn television spectators were only
waiting for the real business of the day - the World Cup Final.
Zubin Mehta once again conducts; this time it is the Los Angeles
Philharmonic Orchestra which gets to play all our favourite tunes. Hard to
avoid the feeling, however, that the Three Tenors phenomenon has probably
outlived its artistic usefulness, notwithstanding the tremendous boost it
has given opera since that starry night at the baths of Caracella in Rome.
Since his Genesis days, Peter Gabriel has had a reputation for being among
the most pioneering of all live rock acts; his Peter Gabriel Secret World
Live (Real World/Virgin) was recorded in Modena, Italy from last year's
international tour, and features a predictable selection of favourites.
Best, perhaps, to see the video, directed by Francois (32 Short Films about
Glenn Gould) Girard and featuring a highly theatrical show co-produced by
Gabriel and Robert Le Page.
Eeriest release of the week is Jeff Buckley's intriguing Grace (Columbia),
for the extraordinary similarity he bears to his late father, the much
under-rated and idiosyncratic singer-songwriter Tim. Seven tracks are
self-penned, while there are fascinating cover versions of Benjamin
Britten's Corpus Christie Carol and Leonard Cohen's Hallelujah.
</TEXT>
