<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / This Week: FT guide to US healthcare debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US government has spent months trying to reform the US healthcare
system, but politicians still spend their time saying that the US has the
best medical care in the world. What's wrong with the current system?
There are two main problems: it costs too much - almost twice as much, in
proportion to the size of the economy, as it does in any other developed
country - and it doesn't cover everyone. Most people get health insurance
from their employer as part of their pay. The elderly are covered by a
government programme called Medicare, and military veterans get care in
Veterans Administration hospitals. Another government programme, called
Medicaid, provides some medical cover for the very poor. But that leaves 35m
to 40m people, most of them working for small businesses or in seasonal
jobs, without any insurance, and the number has been growing steadily. At
the same time, medical expenses have been rising twice as fast as the
general rate of inflation. This puts severe pressure not only on companies
who are paying for insurance, but also on the federal budget. The
Congressional Budget Office last week estimated that Medicare and Medicaid
costs, which today amount to 3.7 per cent of gross domestic product, will
make up 6.2 per cent in ten years time.
What are the ideas for dealing with this?
President Bill Clinton's original plan would have extended health insurance
to everyone by requiring employers to provide insurance to their workers,
and pay at least 80 per cent of the cost. That idea is still in the bill now
up for consideration in the House of Representatives, but no-one gives it
much chance of passing. The Senate, meanwhile, is considering a bill which
draws some elements from the original Clinton plan, but sets itself the less
ambitious goal of covering 95 per cent of the population by the year 2000.
It would offer insurance subsidies, particularly to low income families,
pregnant women and children. If that does not bring enough people into the
health insurance net, a commission would recommend additional measures. And
if Congress failed to act on those, a requirement for employers to provide
insurance to their workers - similar to the Clinton plan but making
employers pay only half the cost - would come into effect as a fallback.
Would this get costs under control?
No-one is very keen on the payment limits the Clinton plan would have
imposed, but not many people are confident that market forces alone are
going to bring medical inflation to heel. The Senate bill proposes its own
curb on prices: a 25 per cent tax on high cost health plans which raise
their prices by more than a target rate. At the same time, any significant
reform is going to cost the government more, at least for the first five or
ten years, because of the money it will take to subsidise insurance for
those who now have none.
Don't the Republicans have any ideas?
The Republicans have been just as divided as the Democrats on what to do
about the health system. Some right wingers have been working to block any
reform at all, and most of the party is now on their side. But some
moderates have been working with Democrats at the centre of the party to
build a 'mainstream coalition', and if a bill is to pass, it will probably
be with their help.
Isn't there anything everyone agrees on?
Yes. Virtually every bill includes measures to stop insurance companies from
turning down an applicant because of an existing medical condition, or from
cancelling their cover when they or a family member gets sick. Premiums
would have to be set on the basis of a whole community, not on how healthy
an applicant appears. Almost everyone wants to raise the tax on a packet of
cigarettes by 45 cents, which would help pay for some of the other reforms.
When is Congress actually going to finish this reform?
Possibly never. The Senate is debating some of the more peripheral issues at
numbing length, while the House hasn't even started debate. If both chambers
pass a bill, they would then have to reconcile their two versions and vote
again on the combined bill. Even the Democrats who want reform now fear they
are running out of time to do that before they have to go home to campaign
for the November elections. That leaves two options: start again next year
with a new Congress, or pass a barebones bill that includes some new rules
for health insurance companies but not much else.
Wouldn't Mr Clinton veto a barebones bill that doesn't cover everyone?
That's what he promised earlier this year. His problem is that no-one
believes he will actually do it if Congress passes anything that could
remotely be described as significant reform.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
