<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Business Travel: Blow for smokers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Four airlines are banning smoking on their transatlantic flights.
The most sweeping change comes from Delta Air Lines which says it will ban
smoking completely on all flights between the US and Europe from January 1,
citing overwhelming support from passengers for the move. It will be the
first US carrier to introduce a total ban on transatlantic flights. From
October 1, American Airlines will extend no-smoking services to two out of
six
daily flights between New York and London and to one out of two flights
between Chicago and London. And from October 30 United Airlines, already
experimenting with no-smoking flights on several international routes, will
extend a smoking ban to two out of three of its flights between New York and
London.
British Airways is also widening a no-smoking experiment on October 30 to
embrace one of its five daily flights between London and New York and all
transatlantic routes to and from Canada.
</TEXT>
