<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Body Shop document pre-empts expected US attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Body Shop International, the cosmetics and toiletries group, has issued a
32-page document pre-empting an expected broadside on it by Mr Jon Entine, a
US journalist, to be published in US journal Business Ethics on September 1.
Mr Gordon Roddick, Body Shop chairman, said: 'The Body Shop can no longer
sit, wait and allow pre-publicity hype to damage its reputation.'
Speculation over the contents of the article has prompted a 24p fall in Body
Shop's share price to 218p.
The company admits that it has not seen the 25,000-word dossier that Mr
Entine has offered to UK newspapers through his agent. However it has seen
an article submitted by Mr Entine to the magazine Vanity Fair, which was not
published. It is this article, Body Shop believes, that is being offered for
serialisation.
Mr Roddick said the article made 'inaccurate and misleading statements which
were very seriously defamatory'.
The Body Shop document attacks what it believes are Mr Entine's arguments.
It says: His statement of the percentage of Body Shop business which comes
from its Trade Not Aid programme with developing countries is false. 'More
importantly his percentages are beside the point,' although such trading 'is
a small part of all our trade'. Accusations about how Body Shop 'stole' its
name and concept are 'demonstrably false'.
Relationships with its franchisees are healthy and prosperous.
The company acknowledges that it uses synthetic, as well as natural
products, and says that it has made no attempt to hide the fact.
It restates its 'powerful commitment to charitable endeavours' and sets out
its 'efforts to be environmentally responsible', acknowledging that 'any
industrial or commercial activity involves some adverse environmental
impact'.
