<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Shoppers make a day of Sunday trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shoppers were out in force yesterday, the first Sunday when stores could
open legally under the Sunday Trading Act to sell a full range of goods.
Many customers would find it difficult to notice the difference because some
of the supermarkets, DIY stores and out-of-town retailers have been opening
on Sundays for some time. Only three big retailers were open for the first
time. They were Marks and Spencer, Waitrose and House of Fraser.
For many people it was a Bank holiday family day out, particularly at
shopping centres where free entertainment and shows were laid on.
Mr Paul Keenan, a spokesman for Gateshead's MetroCentre, which has spent
about Pounds 50,000 on publicity, said: 'It's been very, very busy and we
reckon it could well turn out to be the second-busiest day of the week after
Saturday.'
Trade union concerns about Sunday trading appear to have eased. The chief
fear was that employees might be forced to work on Sunday against their
will, or face the sack.
But all shopworkers, including part-timers and those with less than two
years' service, are protected under the Sunday Trading Act from enforced
Sunday work. The only exceptions are those who contract to work exclusively
on Sundays.
Usdaw, the shopworkers union, is happy with the act but is advising
shopworkers not to sign agreements to work on Sundays unless satisfied with
the terms and conditions.
The Keep Sunday Special Campaign was less phlegmatic. It said many staff
were coming under pressure to agree to work on Sundays.
</TEXT>
