FT  29 AUG 94 / Mexican candidate urges calm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The presidential candidate of Mexico's main leftist opposition party, Mr
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, has urged supporters to obey the law and avoid conflict
in spite of the outcome of the election a week ago, which he has denounced
as fraudulent.
Addressing a crowd of 70,000 in Mexico City's central square, Mr Cardenas
modified his strident rhetoric of early last week. He warned his supporters
not to be provoked into clashes that could lead to bloodshed.
The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) won the election with
50.2 per cent of the votes that were not annulled and 48.8 per cent of all
votes cast, according to official results.
The centre-right National Action Party came second with 26.7 per cent of
valid votes, with Mr Cardenas trailing a poor third on 17.1 per cent.
Mr Cardenas has claimed that many of his supporters were deliberately left
off voting lists and that those from the ruling party were allowed to vote
several times.
The softening of Mr Cardenas's position follows divisions in his own party
on how best to respond to defeat.
While hard-liners have urged massive protests, the moderates in the party
have warned that this would further damage its public image and deflect from
the task of rebuilding.
