<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / Kohl takes the high road in poll campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DORTMUND
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany summoned more tears than cheers with a
calculated, emotional election speech to 17,000 of his Christian Democrat
(CDU) party workers in Dortmund yesterday. No mean hand at jokes and
mud-slinging himself, he left most of the dirty work to his lieutenants.
Mr Theo Waigel, leader of the CDU's sister Christian Social Union, warmed up
the proceedings with a hatchet job on the Social Democrats' would-be finance
minister, Mr Oskar Lafontaine. And Mr Norbert Blum, Chancellor Kohl's fiery
labour minister, sent the crowd home committed to driving out the red peril.
In between, Mr Kohl set out on the 50-day campaign before October's general
election presenting himself and his party as the only guarantors of a secure
economic and political future for Germany - and even Europe.
While his cohorts had given the opposition SPD a fresh coat of red paint,
damning them again as fellow travellers with the Party of Democratic
Socialism, successor to the defunct East German Communist party, Mr Kohl was
more thoughtful. He drew heavily on four years of historic change which had
propelled Germany into a new role in world affairs.
Correcting a blunder he made last week, he yesterday included Moscow in the
list of world capitals with which Germany had broken the ice and built sound
relations during his term. London and Paris were again worth a reference,
but Washington earned a special mention. 'Our connection with America is the
decisive factor for the peace and freedom of the Germans,' he said. However
the main body of his speech was devoted to internal relations, on which his
fourth campaign for the chancellor's job might yet stumble.
'It now remains for us to complete the fulfilment of our dream of German
unity,' he said. The divisive terms 'Ossi' and 'Wessi' had to be driven out
of the public vocabulary. The west had to accept how difficult it was for
easterners to adapt after 50 years of Communist rule. People in the east had
to remember how much better off they now were.
Although weekend polls showed the CDU-CSU and the Free Democrat coalition
partners gaining further support, and making their best combined showing
since April 1992, the spoiling potential of the PDS weighed heavily on
Christian Democrat minds yesterday.
On the one hand, there is a slim chance that the PDS, through a quirk in
electoral law, might gain a handful of seats in parliament without winning
the 5 per cent of the overall vote customarily needed. On the other, Mr Kohl
sees a chance of luring away the more conservative SPD voters to his side.
Party leaders in Saxony-Anhalt caused dismay recently when they established
a minority state government with their traditional Green allies plus the
informal backing of the ex-Communists. While the chancellor's co-speakers
vigorously denounced the prospect of a repetition at federal level, Mr Kohl
played down the perceived threat as an extra incentive for party workers to
fight for every vote.
Although the Free Democrats are showing some gain in support, the chancellor
does not want to leave his chances of a fourth term more in the hands of
fortune than is absolutely necessary.
According to weekend polls, the CDU-CSU would gain 41 per cent of the
popular vote if an election were held now. The union now has one point more
than a month ago, while the SPD is unchanged with 36 per cent. The FDP has 6
per cent and the Greens are steady with 9 per cent.
Much may depend on the 8 per cent balance held by 17 other parties
registered for the election. Half of this largely protest vote currently
lies with the eastern-based PDS.
With 49 more days to go and some 1,000 campaign meetings booked, the CDU's
leaders set off in noisy convoy yesterday. Only the command vessel, Mr Kohl,
was reserving most of its fire. He appeared content that his message - that
Germany had founds its place in the world and needed him to maintain it -
had come across clearly. 'Do our duty,' he said at the close. The cheers
came only slowly, but the eyes in the crowd watered freely. A woman in a
home-knitted yellow suit wiped away copious tears with one hand. In the
other she held aloft a plaster image of the Christ child.
Editorial comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
