<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 94 / US and Cuba to hold talks on refugees
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The US has agreed to hold limited talks with Cuba over the refugee problem
but will not discuss the trade embargo and the US presence on the island at
Guantanamo Bay.
Meanwhile, Cuban president Fidel Castro made a small concession to the US
over the refugees by ordering his police and coastguards to stop unsafe
boats and rafts carrying children from leaving the country, according to a
Cuban Sunday newspaper.
The numbers of refugees has fallen in the past few days as stormy weather in
the Straits of Florida deterred many Cubans from attempting the crossing.
The US coastguard picked up 130 people on Saturday and by midday yesterday
reported they had found no more refugees. The dramatic fall in numbers comes
at the end of a month that has seen 17,100 Cubans flee for the US.
Administration officials acknowledged that the weather had contributed to
the drop, but also said Cubans had come to understand that they would not
get into the country if they fled by boat.
US secretary of state Warren Christopher said more than 200 refugees being
detained at the Guantanamo Bay naval base had asked to be returned to Cuba.
Report, Page 3
</TEXT>
