<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 94 / US to pay arrears on UN peace operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US, after years as the United Nations' chief debtor, intends to pay more
than Dollars 900m (Pounds 580.6m) towards UN peacekeeping costs by the end
of the year, according to Ms Madeleine Albright, US ambassador to the world
body, Reuter reports from New York.
President Bill Clinton planned to sign a bill in the next few days
authorising Dollars 1.2bn for peacekeeping, she said. The funds will cover
peacekeeping arrears until the end of 1994 and allow some revenues for 1995.
UN members owe the organisation Dollars 3.3bn, including Dollars 1.48bn for
peacekeeping and Dollars 835m for regular dues. Of this, US arrears total
Dollars 1.48bn, including Dollars 956m for peacekeeping and Dollars 530m for
the regular budget.
The new US appropriations concern peacekeeping only and not regular dues,
but go a long way to improving the cash flow of the UN. The organisation has
had difficulty in recruiting peacekeepers from poorer countries as there has
been no money to pay them.
Ms Albright said Dollars 335m would be made available to the UN within days
and Dollars 335m would follow in September, contingent on the creation of an
independent inspector-general's office which will monitor waste and
mismanagement. Congress had demanded such action.
The US expects to pay off the remainder of its peacekeeping debt later this
year.
</TEXT>
